Respelling of   Jocelyn ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jocelyn","meanings":["Now normally a girl's name, but in earlier times more often given to boys. It is a transferred use of the English surname, which in turn is derived from an Old French masculine personal name introduced to Britain by the Normans in the form <i>Joscelin</i>. This was originally a derivative, <i>Gautzelin</i>, of the name of a Germanic tribe, the <i>Gauts</i>. The spelling of the first syllable was altered because the name was taken as a double diminutive (with the Old French suffixes <i>-el</i> and <i>-in</i>) of <i>Josce</i> (  see  Joyce  )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":45,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":54,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Joscelyn de Valletort was born about 1170, in North Tawton, Devon, England, his father, Ralph de Valletort, was 32 and his mother, Joan de Dunstanville, was 29. He married Emma Botreaux in 1198, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1230, in Devon, England, at the age of 61, and was buried in Devon, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1170–1230":"umbes 1170–1230","1165–1206":"1165–1206","1170–1188":"1170–1188","1170–1230":"1170–1230","1175–1199":"1175–1199","1210–1259":"1210–1259","–1244":"–1244","114